  <static seed="1036" source="PCC-ORCCA-ed3/BasicAlgebra/GraphingQuadratics/ParabolaIntercepts30.pg">
    <statement><p>Find the <m>y</m>-intercept and any <m>x</m>-intercept(s) of the quadratic curve.</p>
<p><m>{y}={x^{2}-4}</m></p>
<p><m>y</m>-intercept: <fillin characters="16" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
<p><m>x</m>-intercept(s): <fillin characters="17" name="AnSwEr0002"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(0,-4\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(2,0\right), \left(-2,0\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To find a parabola<rsq/>s <m>y</m>-intercept, we substitute <m>x=0</m> into <m>{y}={x^{2}-4}</m>, and we have <m>y=-4</m>.</p>
<p>The parabola<rsq/>s <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>(0,-4)</m>.</p>
<p>To find a parabola<rsq/>s <m>x</m>-intercept, we substitute <m>y=0</m> into <m>{y}={x^{2}-4}</m>, and then solve for <m>x</m>.</p>
<p>For this problem, notice that the polynomial can be factored by the difference of squares formula:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}[t]
   y \amp = {x^{2}-4} \\
   0 \amp = {x^{2}-4} \\
   0 \amp = (x-2)(x + 2) \\
   x-2 \amp = 0      \amp \text{or} \amp \amp  x + 2 \amp = 0 \\
   x       \amp = 2  \amp \text{or} \amp \amp  x \amp = -2 
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The parabola<rsq/>s <m>x</m>-intercepts are <m>(2,0)</m> and <m>(-2,0)</m>.</p>
</solution>
